To create an if/then statement in C, you can use the following syntax:

if (condition) {
  // Code to execute if the condition is true
} else {
  // Code to execute if the condition is false
}

In this example, the condition is enclosed in parentheses and followed by a block of code to execute if the condition is true. If the condition is false, the code in the else block will be executed.

To create a more complex if/then statement, you can use multiple conditions and blocks of code:

if (condition1) {
  // Code to execute if condition1 is true
} else if (condition2) {
  // Code to execute if condition2 is true
} else {
  // Code to execute if neither condition1 nor condition2 is true
}

In this example, if condition1 is true, the code in the first block will be executed. If condition1 is false but condition2 is true, the code in the second block will be executed. If neither condition1 nor condition2 is true, the code in the else block will be executed.

To learn more about if/then statements in C, you can refer to online resources or consult a C programming language reference guide.
